WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
A month or two ago, I was browsing social media,

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:09.000
and I came across this post from Posit on LinkedIn.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:10.000
And it reads,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Are you ready to plan your Posit Conf adventure?

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
The agenda is out now, packed with workshops,

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.000
keynotes, and talks.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.000
And it linked to this chat bot

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:22.000
that allows you to explore the schedule

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
via an interface like Chat2BT.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
This app was built by an attendee to Conf.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:30.000
His name is Sam Palmer.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.000
I think Sam is in the audience.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:34.000
If you're here, can you give us a wave?

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:35.000
There's Sam in the back.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Can we give him a round of applause?

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:45.000
So if anybody gave this chat bot a go before the Conf,

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.000
it's really cool.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:51.000
What Sam did is scraped all the data from the schedule.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And so there's the talks, and the speaker names,

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.000
and the rooms, and the times, and so on and so forth.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.000
And all that gets stuck inside a database.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
And then an LLM has access to this database

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:08.000
via something called Retrieval Augmented Generation, or RAG.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And so that LLM can then search inside of the database

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.000
to respond to your questions.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
So you could say, At what time is Simon Couch speaking?

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:21.000
And hopefully it'll tell you right now.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.000
So this chat bot was built with Elmer and ShinyChat,

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:28.000
which are two R packages, as well as Ragnar,

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
which is an R package supporting RAG inside of R.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.000
And it's something like 20 to 30 lines of R code.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:42.000
So I'm giving a talk.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.000
I see this chat bot.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:47.000
I'm like, I wonder how good it is at surfacing my own stuff.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.000
So I have a little narcissistic moment.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.000
I'm staring at my own reflection.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.000
I say, Is Simon Couch giving a talk?

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:54.000
He says, Yes.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Here's the date and time.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:56.000
So on and so forth.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And I get progressively more and more arcane

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
just to kind of see, like, what are the limits of this?

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And at some point I ask, Are there any talks about evals?

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
This is not really a fair question.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
Evals is sort of slang in the LLM space

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.000
for large language model evaluation.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
But I give it a go anyway.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:17.000
And the model says,

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.000
There's no talk explicitly focused on evals.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
However, you can go watch this other talk,

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:25.000
which happens to be concurrent with mine.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:27.000
So it appears that nobody in this room

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:34.000
typed in that question, or else you might not be here.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:36.000
So again, you can build an app like this

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.000
in something like 20 to 30 lines now.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:41.000
These Elmer and ShinyChat packages are super powerful.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:43.000
And it's really cool how far you can get

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
in such a short amount of time.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
At the same time, once you've started to build out

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
a demo of an AI app, taking that app to production

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.000
requires you to be able to test it

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
and iterate on it quickly.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.000
And it's difficult to do that without an ability

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.000
to evaluate quality and debug issues.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
This is where the Vitals R package comes in,

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
which is a toolkit for LLM evaluation in R.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:13.000
Vitals is an R port of a framework in Python

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.000
called Inspect AI.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.000
So if you're a Pythonista, for the most part in this talk,

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.000
I'm going to refer to Vitals.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
But Inspect AI uses the same language, same framework.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.000
This framework is widely adopted

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.000
by many of the Frontier labs

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.000
as they're building the models themselves.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.000
And also on the Python side,

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.000
we have peers to Elmer and ShinyChat,

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
which are Chatless and appropriately named ShinyChat.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
But I'll focus on Vitals throughout the rest of this talk.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.000
In the rest of the talk,

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.000
I want to remind you of two things.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
The first is that if you're building an LLM app,

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.000
you really should be running evals on it.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And the second thing is that

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
if you have managed to build an LLM app,

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:01.000
you really can do it.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.000
Building evals is straightforward

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
once you have an app built with Elmer.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.000
So let's go ahead and start

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:09.000
on the really-you-really-should-be side.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.000
I hope to convince you

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
that you really should be evaluating your LLM product.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.000
This is a quote from Hemal Hussain,

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
who is a leader in the AI eval space.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:21.000
He writes,

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Like software engineering,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.000
success with AI hinges on how fast you can iterate.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
So whether you're a data scientist or a software engineer,

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
I don't know if immediately you agree with that statement,

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
but I think I might be able to convince you

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
that at some level you do

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
because you adopt tooling that allows you to iterate quickly.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So in software engineering,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
we adopt tools that allow us to make changes,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
like our code editors,

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
and we have autocomplete, maybe LLM-assisted autocomplete,

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.000
and now these agentic editors like Cloud Code

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.000
or Positron Assistant.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
But in addition to these tools to make changes,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
we have tools to evaluate quality, like unit tests.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
So if I go and make some changes

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
in an R package I'm working on,

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
I can both test that that works as I expect it to

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
and didn't break anything else in the process.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
And we also have tools to help us debug issues,

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
so like the debugger and rep practices,

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
and so on and so forth.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.000
In AI, we also have all sorts of tools

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
that allow us to make these sorts of changes to our apps.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.000
So we can engineer the system prompt,

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.000
we can put together this rag tool,

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
like was under the hood in this conf chatbot app,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
and so on and so forth,

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
and there's a lot of effort in this part of the space.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.000
What about those other two steps?

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
It's mostly like a vibe check.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
So I make some changes to the prompt,

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
and I ask a couple questions,

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:51.000
and I'm like, that seems reasonable.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And so we have a look-see,

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:57.000
and if you've tried to bring your AI demos to production before,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.000
you know that this can kind of become

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
a whack-a-mole sort of process,

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
where you might resolve one issue,

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.000
and at the same time, you accidentally introduce another one.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.000
And so Vitals allows us to iterate more quickly

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
by giving us tools to evaluate quality and debug issues.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
I'll show you in a moment that when you run evals with Vitals,

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
you get these higher-level summaries

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
of how well your app is performing on different axes,

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
and when there are issues,

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
you have the ability to drill down in the details

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.000
to debug what went wrong.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
So hopefully I've convinced you that this is something worth doing.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Now I want to convince you that if you're a user of Elmer

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
and you've made a chatbot already,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:46.000
you do have the ability to make some evals as well.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:49.000
And that's because we designed Vitals

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.000
with Elmer specifically in mind,

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
so that once you have an app,

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
you can just plug it right into Vitals,

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
and it's plug-and-play.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
To talk through that process,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
we'll talk through the three pieces that compose an evaluation,

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
which is a dataset, a solver, and a scorer.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
And to do so, we'll use that app from SAM

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
that is the conf chatbot app.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
So first let's talk about a dataset.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Minimally, datasets are just a data frame

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
that have two columns.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
The first column is an input,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
and this is something that a user might ask of your app.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
So for example, in that last slide,

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
I said, are there any talks about evals?

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And then the second column in that data frame is a target,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.000
and a target gives you corresponding grading guidance

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.000
for that given input,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:44.000
or maybe even the answer itself.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
And so a target in that last example might be,

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:49.000
yes, Simon Couch will be giving a talk

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:53.000
called, Is That LLM Feature Any Good?

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:58.000
So I know this is a conference about serious data science,

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:00.000
and I'm an R package developer,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
so I take data structures really seriously and yada yada.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:13.000
You can just use Google Sheets. It's okay.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
It's really, like, sort of painful

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
to type out these long structured text response

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.000
inside of a call to data.frame or tbl or trbl

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.000
or whatever it may be.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:25.000
This is, like, a perfect use case

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
for something like a Google Sheet or an Excel file.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
So again, this is just a data frame with two columns.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
One is the input, one is the target,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:38.000
and then you can read that into R or Python after.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.000
So for example, another possible input you might ask is,

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.000
are there any sessions about causal inference?

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
And your grading guidance would be,

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
yes, there's this workshop called

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
Causal Inference in R by Malcolm and Lucy.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So we have our data set.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:59.000
The next step is building a solver.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
If you've built a chat app with Elmer,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
you know it looks roughly something like this.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
You can load the Elmer package

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
and then initialize a client,

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
which is just a specification

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
of how you connect to a given LLM.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
So if I run chat open AI,

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.000
I've connected by default to GPT 4.1,

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.000
but you can connect to Anthropic or Bedrock

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
or Snowflake or Databricks

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:25.000
or whatever it may be with Elmer.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.000
And then you make your changes.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.000
You write out a system prompt and you incorporate tools,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
like in this conf chatbot app,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:35.000
this is a rag tool, and so on and so forth.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.000
And once you're finished with that,

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.000
you just drop it into live browser.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
This is a function in Elmer that makes use of ShinyChat

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
and puts your client into a container

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
that looks something like chatgpt.com.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.000
So when I say that evaluation with vitals is plug-and-play,

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
I mean that you can just plop your client

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.000
right inside to vitals, and that's your solver.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
So you're done.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
So up to this point now, the data set has two columns.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
The data set has the input

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
and then the corresponding grading guidance

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
for that input, which is the target.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.000
We pass the input from the data set to the solver,

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
so we ask the solver, are there any talks about evals,

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
and we get some response back.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:26.000
And so up to this point, we now have three data points.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
One way that we can score this

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.000
is by concatenating all these together in a string.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
You might have known I was going here.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
And we can say you're assessing a submitted answer

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
on a given task based on a criterion.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.000
Here's the task.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
Here's the submission, which is the response from the solver.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
And here's the criteria, which is that target grading guidance.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.000
Does the submission meet the criterion?

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
And you pass that along to some LLM.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
The first time I saw this,

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.000
I definitely had this sort of reaction,

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
like, are we really serious?

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
This is the way that we're going to do this?

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
There's some strong empirical evidence

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
that this is generally something that works

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:12.000
and tends to agree well with human raters

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
when these systems are designed well.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
So on the Vitals package website,

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
as well as the Inspect AI website,

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
there's all sorts of guidance

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
about how to put together these systems thoughtfully.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
But for now, we'll just take it for granted

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.000
that, yes, this is the way that we're going to do it.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
If you're like, absolutely not,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
this is not the way that this is going to go,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
there are certain solvers and LLM systems

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
that you don't need this LLM,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
as a judge is what they call it,

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
where you use an LLM itself to score the response.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And so if you're like, no way, that's not a deal-breaker.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
There's a way to make that happen.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:51.000
But now we have a data set, a solver, and a score.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.000
The container for these three objects

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
in Vitals and Inspect is called a task.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.000
And so we can use Google Sheets 4

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
to read in that spreadsheet that we put on online,

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.000
and then we situate the data set, the solver,

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.000
and the score inside of this task.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
This task has a bunch of methods.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
One of them is called eval,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
which first runs all the solver inputs in parallel

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:19.000
and then scores all of them in parallel.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
And so for these eight inputs,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
this took something like 11 seconds, 12 seconds.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:31.000
In addition to a modified version of the task itself,

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:35.000
something that both Vitals and Inspect give back to you

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
is this thing called the log viewer.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
And the log viewer is sort of a foundational tool

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.000
for both evaluating quality and debugging issues.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
So at the highest level, you get these scores,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
like the accuracy.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.000
So in this case, in six of eight responses,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
the solver from this conf chatbot app

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
was rated as being correct.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
And we can scroll down through this app

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.000
until we see where some sort of issue came up.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
So this score here was marked as incorrect

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
with a red circle.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
And I can click into this and drill down into the details

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
to figure out what went wrong.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.000
So the user says, will there be any talks

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:16.000
about making R data packages?

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
The LLM then chooses to use this RAG tool

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:22.000
to go search for relevant speakers.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
And the model doesn't find anything

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.000
that it particularly thinks is compelling,

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
but it tosses something out anyway.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.000
And it turns out that the target we were looking for

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:35.000
is a talk from Kelly McConville this afternoon

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:38.000
called Teaching Data Sharing Through R Data Packages.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.000
And so since that LLM system didn't surface

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.000
the response that we were interested in doing,

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.000
this is marked as incorrect.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
I hope in this talk that I've managed to convince you

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.000
that when it comes to running evals on your LLM apps,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
you really should be doing it,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.000
and also it is something that you're capable of doing.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
If you are building LLM apps already,

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
this is really something you should be doing.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.000
And if you're already able to do that,

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.000
you can build evals.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.000
I'm very grateful for the opportunity to be here.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
If you want to learn more about vitals,

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
if you want to see the source code for these slides,

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
or some resources and quotes

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
that I've pointed to throughout the talk,

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:28.000
you can go to github.com slash simonpcouch slash conf dash 25.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
Thank you.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
applause

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
Thanks, Simon.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
We do have some time for questions.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
First one.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
Should we view evals as a replacement

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:47.000
or complement to vibes, as in vibe coding?

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.000
Yeah, this is quite the debate.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
There was this interview with, like,

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
the person who wrote Cloud Code

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
that came out a week or two ago,

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
and at some point in this interview, he's like,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
yeah, we tried evals, and I don't know about that.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
Are they a replacement for vibes?

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
I think, especially early on in the process,

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
as you're building these demos,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
like, the vibes are the thing to focus on.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
And only once you start to discover these patterns

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
where you see the same sorts of errors again and again

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
are points where you might want to start

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
introducing those evals to making sure

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
you have an eye out for them.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
Next question.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:29.000
When you get bad evals, how do you improve the output?

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:32.000
When you get bad evals, how do you improve the output?

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
This is, like, really where a lot of the focus

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
in the LLM space is going right now

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
is, like, these changes that you can make to the app.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:43.000
So the places that we tend to focus on

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.000
when we're advising people

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
on where to start with building LLM apps

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
is stuffing a bunch of stuff into the context

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
and then giving LLMs the ability

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.000
to surface information, run code that they need to

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
to answer your question using tools.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
The LMR and chat list packages

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
try to make it as easy as possible

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.000
to iterate on those system prompts in your tools,

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
so that's a good place to start.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
All right. Thank you so much, Simon.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
Let's thank Simon again.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
Thank you.

